Business Analytics Case Study - Fitness Mobile App

By Ishack Mougamadou

The probability of a customer willing to pay for a fitness app is defined by the following factors, income, number of gym visits and hours spent at the gym. This analysis was done to identify the most significant factor that influences whether a customer would pay for a mobile fitness app.

This analysis was run on R Studio Version 1.1.456: Windows 10 Intel i3 4GB RAM

Load Libraries

library(rpart) # Decision Tree library

Frequency Distribution Graphs

#Created a frequency distribution graph for each of the numeric variables.

All the factors showed that the residuals are non-normally distributed.

plot(diagnostic_plot) # plot the diagnostic plots

##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  Incomes
## W = 0.85629, p-value = 2.039e-08

P-value confirmed that the residuals are non-normally distrubuted.

Boxplot

boxplot(Incomes~PayOrNot, col=c("mistyrose","powderblue"),
        main="Income vs Pay or Not", ylab="Income  (Thousands)", xlab="Pay Or Not")  # Boxplot of Pay Status based on Income

The boxplot indicated that those who have an income above 90,000 agreed to pay for the mobile fitness app, while the majority of those with an income below 90,000 declined to pay for the mobile fitness app. There was one outlier customer.

Correlations Plots

# Income vs Hours
model_income=(Incomes~Hours) 
plot(model_income, pch = 20, col= "blue", main= "Income Vs Hours", ylab = "Income    (Thousands)", xlab= "Hours Spent in the Gym")
abline (lm(model_income), col="red")

There was a positive relationship between the income and the hours spent at the gym.

# Income vs Gym Visits
model1=(Incomes~GymVisits)
plot(model1, pch = 20, col= "blue", main= "Income Vs Gym Visits", ylab = "Income    (Thousands)", xlab= "Number of Gym Visits")
abline (lm(model1), col="red")

There was a positive relationship between the income and the number of visits to the gym.

Pearson Correlation Tests

# Pearson correlation between income and fitness visits
cor.test(Incomes,GymVisits, method = "pearson") 
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  Incomes and GymVisits
## t = 1.4068, df = 98, p-value = 0.1626
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.05730557  0.32804860
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.1406962

There was no statistically significant difference between the income and the number of gym visits.

cor.test(Incomes,Hours, method = "pearson") 
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  Incomes and Hours
## t = 13.461, df = 98, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.7237052 0.8651306
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.8056072

However,there was a statistically significant difference between the income and the number of hours spent at the gym (P-value = < 2.2e-16).

ANOVA Analysis

anova_model=lm(Incomes~GymVisits*Hours*PayOrNot)
anova1=anova(anova_model)
anova1

The most significant difference in terms of the income was the number of gym visits and the customers decision to pay or not for the mobile fitness app.

DT=rpart.plot(Tree_analysis,extra = 4)

The decision tree analysis indicated that income influenced the customers decision the most. Also, the state where they lived also played a vital role in the decision-making process.

Conclusion

In conclusion, the hours of a customer is the most influential factor when deciding if a customer is willing to pay for the mobile fitness app. This decision is because Income determines how many times a customer visits the gym (Gym Visits), which ultimately determines whether the customer will pay for the mobile fitness app or not (P- Value = 5.855e-07, the most statistically significant P-value).
